editorial:
**Classic merge sort — divide & conquer template**.

1. **Divide**: split into halves around mid.
2. **Conquer**: recursively merge-sort each half.
3. **Combine**: two-pointer merge into a fresh array.

```javascript
function mergeSortOrders(orders) {
  if (orders.length <= 1) return orders.slice();
  const mid = orders.length >> 1;
  const left = mergeSortOrders(orders.slice(0, mid));
  const right = mergeSortOrders(orders.slice(mid));
  const merged = [];
  let i = 0, j = 0;
  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (left[i] <= right[j]) merged.push(left[i++]);
    else merged.push(right[j++]);
  }
  while (i < left.length) merged.push(left[i++]);
  while (j < right.length) merged.push(right[j++]);
  return merged;
}
```

**Recurrence**: T(n) = 2·T(n/2) + Θ(n).

**Master theorem**: a=2, b=2, f(n)=Θ(n), c_crit=log_2 2 = 1. Case 2 ⇒ T(n) = Θ(n log n).

**Space**: O(n) for the merge buffers + O(log n) recursion depth.

Stable sort because we use `<=` in the merge — equal keys keep left-side priority.

