editorial:
**Quickselect**: partition the array around a pivot. After partition, the pivot is at its final sorted index. Compare that index to the target — recurse only into the relevant side, **never both**. This is the divide-and-conquer twist that drops the cost from O(n log n) (full sort) to expected O(n).

```javascript
function kthLargest(orders, k) {
  const arr = orders.slice();
  const target = arr.length - k; // k-th largest = (n-k)-th smallest, 0-indexed
  function partition(lo, hi) {
    const pivIdx = lo + Math.floor(Math.random() * (hi - lo + 1));
    [arr[pivIdx], arr[hi]] = [arr[hi], arr[pivIdx]];
    const pivot = arr[hi];
    let i = lo;
    for (let j = lo; j < hi; j++) {
      if (arr[j] < pivot) {
        [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]];
        i++;
      }
    }
    [arr[i], arr[hi]] = [arr[hi], arr[i]];
    return i;
  }
  let lo = 0, hi = arr.length - 1;
  while (lo <= hi) {
    const p = partition(lo, hi);
    if (p === target) return arr[p];
    if (p < target) lo = p + 1; else hi = p - 1;
  }
  return -1;
}
```

**Recurrence (avg, random pivot)**: T(n) = T(n/2) + Θ(n) ⇒ Θ(n).

**Master theorem**: a=1, b=2, f(n)=Θ(n), c_crit=0, f dominates ⇒ Case 3 ⇒ T(n)=Θ(n).

Worst case (adversarial pivot): T(n) = T(n-1) + Θ(n) = Θ(n²). Random/median-of-three keeps that astronomically unlikely.

