editorial:
**Bentley's divide & conquer**:

```javascript
function maxSubarrayDC(values) {
  function helper(lo, hi) {
    if (lo === hi) return values[lo];
    const mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
    const leftBest = helper(lo, mid);
    const rightBest = helper(mid + 1, hi);
    let leftSum = -Infinity, sum = 0;
    for (let i = mid; i >= lo; i--) { sum += values[i]; leftSum = Math.max(leftSum, sum); }
    let rightSum = -Infinity; sum = 0;
    for (let i = mid + 1; i <= hi; i++) { sum += values[i]; rightSum = Math.max(rightSum, sum); }
    const crossBest = leftSum + rightSum;
    return Math.max(leftBest, rightBest, crossBest);
  }
  return helper(0, values.length - 1);
}
```

**Recurrence**: T(n) = 2·T(n/2) + Θ(n) — the cross-sum pass is linear.

**Master theorem**: a=2, b=2, f(n)=Θ(n), c_crit=1, Case 2 ⇒ T(n) = Θ(n log n).

**Why D&C and not Kadane?** Kadane is Θ(n) and is the right choice in production. The D&C version generalizes to harder problems (e.g., max sum in 2D, online updates with segment trees) where the recurrence pattern matters.

