editorial:
**Operator-split D&C**: every operator is a valid root for an expression tree. Take the cross-product of (results-of-left, results-of-right) for each operator and combine.

```javascript
function diffWaysToCompute(expr) {
  const memo = new Map();
  function solve(s) {
    if (memo.has(s)) return memo.get(s);
    const out = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
      const c = s[i];
      if (c === '+' || c === '-' || c === '*') {
        const L = solve(s.slice(0, i));
        const R = solve(s.slice(i + 1));
        for (const x of L) for (const y of R) {
          if (c === '+') out.push(x + y);
          else if (c === '-') out.push(x - y);
          else out.push(x * y);
        }
      }
    }
    if (out.length === 0) out.push(parseInt(s, 10));
    memo.set(s, out);
    return memo.get(s);
  }
  return solve(expr).sort((a, b) => a - b);
}
```

**Recurrence**: with n operators, T(n) ≈ Σ T(k)·T(n-1-k). Without memo this is the **Catalan number** C_n ≈ 4^n / n^(3/2). With memoization on substrings the work collapses to polynomial. Master theorem doesn't apply cleanly here (non-balanced split); the bound is the Catalan-style recurrence solved by generating functions.

The test compares sorted output for determinism; the problem statement says any order is OK.

