**Idea**: at each step compare `a[i + k/2 - 1]` and `b[j + k/2 - 1]`. The smaller side's first k/2 elements can't contain the k-th overall (they are dominated). Skip them, reduce k, recurse.

```javascript
function kthSmallestTwoSorted(a, b, k) {
  function solve(i, j, k) {
    if (i >= a.length) return b[j + k - 1];
    if (j >= b.length) return a[i + k - 1];
    if (k === 1) return Math.min(a[i], b[j]);
    const half = Math.floor(k / 2);
    const ai = i + half - 1 < a.length ? a[i + half - 1] : Infinity;
    const bj = j + half - 1 < b.length ? b[j + half - 1] : Infinity;
    if (ai <= bj) return solve(i + half, j, k - half);
    return solve(i, j + half, k - half);
  }
  return solve(0, 0, k);
}
```

**Recurrence**: T(k) = T(k/2) + Θ(1).

**Master theorem**: a=1, b=2, f(k)=Θ(1) ⇒ Case 2 ⇒ T(k) = Θ(log k) ⊆ Θ(log(m+n)).

